Portfolio managers cut their net long position in Brent by almost 50 million barrels in the week to May 22, the largest one-week reduction since before the rally started in June 2017. Recent sharp falls in oil prices, especially Brent, are therefore not surprising, given that fund managers have been steadily liquidating long positions and adding shorts for more than a month. http://fingfx.thomsonreuters.com/gfx/ce/6/1262/1260/CFTC%20AND%20ICE%20COMMITMENTS%20OF%20TRADERS.pdf

Saudis want to $80 and their effort to reach that level is advancing but may take longer than the month or so until June 22. Certainly one can see enough actual and potential political conflicts to justify the rise. World demand also is a positive factor in petro prices. Really the question is when will we see $80 not if we will see $80.
At fast pace, price of oil can rise $10 per barrel in a month. Given current price, and rising prices as entering summer, expect that by end of June will be on higher range.
As always with market prices, I am starting from the view that prices are volatile and probability distributions ought to be wide.
